  "prompt": "How do artists who work under anonymous pseudonyms report their taxes?",
  "response": "Artists who work under anonymous pseudonyms still need to report their income and pay taxes just like any other individual. Here\u2019s how they typically handle it:\n\n1. **Use Their Legal Name**: When filing taxes, the artist must use their legal name, not their pseudonym. The IRS requires individuals to report their income and file taxes using their legal identity.\n\n2. **Business Entity**: Some artists create a business entity (e.g., LLC, corporation) under their pseudonym to manage their art-related income and expenses. In this case, the business files taxes separately, and the artist reports their income from the business on their personal tax return.\n\n3. **Schedule C (Self-Employment Income)**: If the artist operates a sole proprietorship under their pseudonym, they report their income and expenses on **Schedule C** (Form 1040) when filing their personal tax return. The pseudonym can be listed as the \"business name,\" but the artist\u2019s legal name is still required.\n\n4. **1099 Forms**: If the artist earns income through a pseudonym, clients or platforms may issue a **Form 1099** to the artist using their legal name or their business entity\u2019s name. The artist ensures this income is reported on their tax return.\n\n5. **Track Income and Expenses**: Artists must keep accurate records of all income earned under their pseudonym, as well as any deductible expenses (e.g., art supplies, studio rent, marketing).\n\n6. **State and Local Taxes**: Depending on the jurisdiction, artists may also need to report their income for state and local tax purposes, following similar guidelines.\n\n7. **Consult a Tax Professional**: Given the complexity of income earned under pseudonyms and potential deductions, many artists consult with a tax professional or accountant to ensure compliance and optimize their tax strategy.\n\nThe idea is that while an artist may work anonymously or under a pseudonym, the IRS still needs to track and tax the income associated with their legal identity.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
